{"type":"message","id":"6b121b5b","parentId":"a5498986","timestamp":"2026-04-07T16:30:59.825Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"One night in 1936, at the Berlin Olympics, Jesse Owens stood at the long jump line. He'd already fouled twice. One more mistake and his Olympic dream was over.\n\nWatching from the side was Luz Long, his German rival, the man everyone expected to win. Instead of waiting for Owens to fail, he walked over. Quietly, he gave Owens one small piece of advice: jump an inch behind the line. Just make it count.\n\nOwens did. He qualified, went on to win gold. And after the final jump, Luz Long was the very first person to walk over and shake his hand.\n\nThis is the quiet truth: greatness isn't beating someone. It's helping them become their best, even when they stand across from you.\n\nGoodnight everyone. Sleep well. 🖤"}],"api":"openai-responses","provider":"openclaw","model":"delivery-mirror","usage":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":0,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1775579459825}}
